Model architecture

Histogram-based Gradient Boosting Regressor (sklearn HistGradientBoostingRegressor)
predicting hourly bike demand per station.

Features

- Time: hour, weekday, weekend, working_day
- Holidays: one-hot encoded holiday names (4 columns)
- Demand averages (target encoding): city_hour_mean, city_weekday_mean
  with global fallback for unseen cities
- Weather: temperature, humidity, apparent_temperature, precipitation,
  rain, snowfall, cloud_cover, wind_speed
- POI/Infrastructure: bike_lane_length, park_area, university_count,
  office_count, retail_count, restaurant_cafe_count, transit_stop_count,
  distance_to_nearest_rail_station, distance_to_city_center

Design Decisions

- Station ID and city are NOT used as direct features to enable generalization
  to unseen cities (city3, city4).
- Training data includes demand=0 rows (active-window grid with 24h buffer
  per station) to match the evaluation format. We took the first and last rides time stamps of staions 
  samples and filled all missing hours in between and a buffer 24 hours with demand = 0.
- Out-of-range values replaced with column median (computed on train only).
- Missing POI/location values imputed with city median, fallback to global median.
- We ran a matrix of hyperparameters ranges and continued with the best combination.

Hyperparameters

- max_iter: 1000
- learning_rate: 0.05
- max_depth: 10
- max_leaf_nodes: 127
- min_samples_leaf: 20

Reproducing

From the submission folder:

    cd submissions/my_team
    python train.py

This reads ../../dataset/train_set.csv, trains the model from scratch,
and saves weights.joblib. Takes approximately 5 minutes.

Validation Performance

MAE on local time-based validation split (last 20% of data):
- Overall: 0.964
- City 1: 1.228
- City 2: 0.654
- City 3: 0.995